/a></div></div><h3><em>MCU low-power features such as built-in energy harve=
sting help optimize applications where long battery life is important.</em>=
</h3>
<p><em>Masamitsu Muratani, <strong>Renesas</strong></em><br>
The spectacular growth of the Internet of Things (IoT) is driving the need =
for devices that are smarter, faster, and can last for long periods on smal=
l and inexpensive batteries. To meet such requirements, Renesas has develop=
ed a new, <a href=3D"https://www.renesas.com/products/microcontrollers-micr=
oprocessors/re-cortex-m-ultra-low-power-sotb-mcus" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D=
"noopener">ultra-efficient microcontroller (MCU) power management architect=
ure</a>. This architecture is based on Silicon on Thin Buried oxide (SOTB) =
process technology with the widely used Cortex M series CPU cores at its he=
art.</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_12649" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-1264=
9" style=3D"width: 500px" class=3D"wp-caption alignleft"><img decoding=3D"a=
sync" class=3D"size-full wp-image-12649 perfmatters-lazy entered pmloaded" =
src=3D"https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/sotb-=
sized.jpg" alt=3D"SOTB comparisoni" width=3D"500" height=3D"334" data-src=
=3D"https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/sotb-siz=
ed.jpg" data-srcset=3D"https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-content/uploa=
ds/2022/02/sotb-sized.jpg 500w, https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-cont=
ent/uploads/2022/02/sotb-sized-300x200.jpg 300w" data-sizes=3D"(max-width: =
500px) 100vw, 500px" data-ll-status=3D"loaded"><figcaption id=3D"caption-at=
tachment-12649" class=3D"wp-caption-text">How current consumption of RE MCU=
s, fabbed using the SOTB process, compares with that of chips fabricated us=
ing conventional IC process dimensions. The Renesas RE MCU family is also c=
ertified by EEMBC (Embedded Microprocessor Benchmark Consortium) to have a =
score of 705 for the ULPMark-CP ULPMark benchmark, which quantifies many as=
pects of ultra-low power MCUs.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The Silicon on Thin Buried Oxide (SOTB) process is proprietary transisto=
r technology from Renesas based on SOI (Silicon on Insulator) wafers. The b=
enefit of SOTB is it can greatly reduce both active and standby current, wh=
ich are normally traded off against each other. SOTB has the low-leakage be=
nefits of larger geometries, with the high-performance and low active curre=
nt benefits of smaller silicon geometries.</p>
<p>In SOTB chips, a thin insulating oxide film (BOX, buried oxide) is depos=
ited on top of the base silicon substrate. Next, a thin silicon layer with =
no impurities is deposited on top of the BOX insulator layer to form a dopa=
ntless channel transistor under the gate, a structure that reduces threshol=
d voltage variance, and thus enables a low operating voltage.</p>
<p>The net effect of the BOX insulating layer and the dopantless channel is=
 high performance, low-voltage operation with both low leakage current and =
low operational current. To further optimize performance while reducing lea=
kage during standby, a bias voltage may be applied to the base silicon subs=
trate beneath the BOX insulator layer. (As an aside, SOC designers can mix =
the use of SOTB and standard CMOS bulk transistors as needed to optimize pe=
rformance, efficiency, and adapt to existing IP designs. Examples of bulk t=
ransistor use can be found in I/O ports, charge pumps, and specific analog =
functions.)</p>
<h5>Estimating power consumption</h5>
<figure id=3D"attachment_12651" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-1265=
1" style=3D"width: 476px" class=3D"wp-caption alignleft"><img decoding=3D"a=
sync" class=3D"size-full wp-image-12651 perfmatters-lazy entered pmloaded" =
src=3D"https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/IoT-p=
ower-sized.jpg" alt=3D"IoT power sources" width=3D"476" height=3D"200" data=
-src=3D"https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/IoT-=
power-sized.jpg" data-srcset=3D"https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-cont=
ent/uploads/2022/02/IoT-power-sized.jpg 476w, https://www.microcontrollerti=
ps.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/IoT-power-sized-300x126.jpg 300w" data-si=
zes=3D"(max-width: 476px) 100vw, 476px" data-ll-status=3D"loaded"><figcapti=
on id=3D"caption-attachment-12651" class=3D"wp-caption-text">How power cons=
umption typically breaks down in a conventional IoT application characteriz=
ed by sensing, data collection, and transmitting data.</figcaption></figure=
>
<p>The typical way of computing the power consumption of a system is to fir=
st decompose the operation of the system for each task and model the operat=
ion time and electrical current each task requires. Additionally, the power=
 assessment process requires defining the cycle time of each task, that is =
the standby time paired with the operation time.</p>
<p><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignleft size-full wp-image-12650 perf=
matters-lazy entered pmloaded" src=3D"https://www.microcontrollertips.com/w=
p-content/uploads/2022/02/current-profile-sized.jpg" alt=3D"IoT current con=
sumption profile" width=3D"390" height=3D"244" data-src=3D"https://www.micr=
ocontrollertips.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/current-profile-sized.jpg" d=
ata-srcset=3D"https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/0=
2/current-profile-sized.jpg 390w, https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2022/02/current-profile-sized-300x188.jpg 300w" data-sizes=3D=
"(max-width: 390px) 100vw, 390px" data-ll-status=3D"loaded">For IoT devices=
, three tasks typically define most operations: sensing, data processing, a=
nd communication processing. The power consumption of the entire system can=
 be thought of as the sum of the power consumption of these tasks.</p>
<p>It=E2=80=99s evident that the ratio of the active and standby mode times=
 is an important parameter. Important, too, is the magnitude of the electri=
c current in the active and standby modes: The total power consumption of a=
 task is expressed by the area of its current profile. Dividing the total p=
rofile area by time yields the average current. A design that reduces the a=
rea of the electric current profile is also a design that minimizes power c=
onsumption.</p>
<p>The SOTB process technology greatly reduces both active and static power=
 consumption. The digital functions of the device=E2=80=93such as the SRAM,=
 CPU, and peripheral functions=E2=80=93are supplied with a regulated intern=
al voltage and are implemented by transistors based on SOTB technology.</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_12652" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-1265=
2" style=3D"width: 500px" class=3D"wp-caption alignleft"><img decoding=3D"a=
sync" class=3D"size-full wp-image-12652 perfmatters-lazy entered pmloaded" =
src=3D"https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/mcu-e=
xternal-sized.jpg" alt=3D"MCU with external supplies" width=3D"500" height=
=3D"410" data-src=3D"https://www.microcontrollertips.com/wp-content/uploads=
/2022/02/mcu-external-sized.jpg" data-srcset=3D"https://www.microcontroller=
